title: For Sale:  Springfield M1903 w/ M1913 Warner & Swasey Sniper
postcontent: This is an excellent condition WWI vintage U. S. Springfield Model 1903 sniper rifle that is fitted with a “Warner & Swasey Telescopic Musket Sight, Model of 1913”. This original M1913 scope/base combination is numbered 6141 on the left side of the scope receiver and retains approximately 95% of its original black enamel finish. All surfaces and adjustment wheels clean with no corrosion. The sight is complete with the original rubber eye piece. The optics are in fairly clear condition. The crosshair reticle is intact as are the three stadia lines for estimating distance. The left side of the receiver is fitted with the original Warner & Swasey mounting bracket secured by three screws. The left side of the stock is inletted to clear the feet of the scope mounting bracket. The bracket screws are flush with the inside of the receiver and are staked in place to rifle receiver. The rifle’s s/n is 577970. According to Bruce Canfield’s U.S. INFANTRY WEAPONS OF THE FIRST WORLD WAR (page 106), M1913 sights in the serial number 22XX to 69XX range were fitted to rifle serial numbers in the 577XXX to 935XXX range. The inside of the telescopic sight mount is not stamped with the rifle s/n indicating that the scope is an “unissued” example. The barrel is roll-stamped "S A" immediately behind the rear sight base above the ordnance "flaming bomb" insignia and the date "7-16" which is about two years later than the receiver date, indicating that the rifle was re-barreled at some point. The bore is in excellent condition. An "H" is stamped on the underside of the bayonet lug. The steel lot code "C 7" is stamped on the underside of the bolt safety lug. The rear sight is the correct 2750-yard folding leaf type that is adjustable for elevation and windage. The trigger is grooved with a cross-hatched tip. The oil-finished, black walnut, "S" type stock with the high hump handguard are in excellent condition. The final inspection cartouche "J.F.C." (Inspector J.F. Coyle) in a rectangle is stamped on the left side of the stock behind the magazine cut-off. An encircled "P" proof mark is stamped on the underside of the stock behind the trigger guard. A stock is stamped “21” below the trigger guard. A "R" sub-inspection mark is stamped in the cut-off recess of the stock. The buttplate has fine checkering. A vintage WWI type nickel-plated oiler and thong case is located in the butt trap recess. Included with the rifle is a scarce, excellent condition, russet leather, case for the Model 1913 Warner & Swasey Musket Sight. The back side of the case is stamped with the manufacturer’s name DIAMOND “D”/ logo/ and initials “A.B.D.” It does not have the shoulder strap or adjustment tool in the front pocket. These rifles are extremely scarce in the well documented serial number range and in this exceptional overall condition.
